Part One: Data Collection¶

We will be using two datasets in our tutorial:

1. Maryland Median Household Income By Year With Margin Of Error: 2010-2018 
    https://opendata.maryland.gov/Demographic/Maryland-Median-Household-Income-By-Year-With-Marg/bvk4-qsxs

2. Annual House Price Index by County
    https://www.fhfa.gov/DataTools/Downloads/Pages/House-Price-Index-Datasets.aspx#atvol

When researching datasets to use for our analysis, we were conflicted about what measure to use to account for housing rates. If we used the average housing price, the data would be susceptible to heavy skewing by outliers. While the median sale price is a good measure of the typical sale price, it is not very useful for measuring home price appreciation because it is dependent on the number of houses sold in a certain range, rather than the average value increase of homes. For example, if more lower-end homes were sold in a certain year, the median would decrease, even if the value of each home increased. According to the Center for Real Estate at Wichita State University, home price indexes "attempt to address this using statistical techniques to provide a constant quality measure of home price appreciation" (CRE, 2020). According to Wikipedia, a House Price Index (HPI) is a tool that measures the price changes of residential housing as a percentage change from some specific base start date (which has a HPI of 100).

We will use this data to analyze the relationship between HPI and personal income in Maryland.

We simply used Pandas to bring the data in and store the data in Pandas dataframes. For the housing dataset, used pandas to read an Excel file, using openxyl, which is a pythonlibrary to read/write Excel 2010 xlsx/xlsm/xltx/xltm files. For the income dataset, we used pandas to read in the CSV(comma-separated values) file.

Part Two: Data Management¶

Tidy Data¶

Then, we tidied the data by removing unnecessary information, handling improper types, as well as organizing by the most relevant information.

The housing dataset contained information about every state in the US. We first filtered to include entries in Maryland. Then, we noticed that the year and HPI with 2000 base columns had non-numeric entries, so we casted them to numeric values for easier manipulation in graph visualizations. Finally, we filtered out the data to only include information from the year 2000 and ahead, as the latest available base HPI of 100 was in 2000, and the income data we would compare against begins in 2010. Later in our code we adjust the housing frame to align with the income years.

Part Three: Exploratory Data Analysis¶

Exploratory data analysis(EDA) is used toanalyzeand investigatedatasets and summarize their main characteristics, usually by employingdatavisualization methods. EDA is critical to finding patterns in datasets that can be used for further investigation. Below, we will explore the two datasets in our project.

First, we will explore the HPI data. We created line graphs to visualize the HPI change overtime in each county. Just by first glance at the graphs, we can see that there are shared characteristics across all of the counties. Across counties, the HPI typically reaches a peak between the years 2005 and 2007, and dips in the year 2012. The 2012 dip aligns with the general state of the US economy; drowning in debt. According to The Balance, at the end of2012, the U.S. debt was 16.05 trillion dollars. That made the debt-to-GDP ratio 100 percent, higher than at any time since World War II. Debt was driven by government spending and reduced revenue from taxes, thanks to sloweconomicgrowth. The Fiscal Year2012budget deficit was $1.077 trillion.

In the following code, we calculate the percentage change in HPI for each county by year. We use a 2-dimensional array to store these calculations. The first layer of the array contains the different counties, and the inner array for each county contain the percent change over each year. For each year, we calculate the percent change to the next year, and append it to the inner array. Our code accounts for when counties change in the dataset as well as the size of the dataset.

In [129]:
# To get the percentage change for every county by year. The overarching array represents the different counties, and the inner arrays are the percentage changes
# every year for that particular county
percent_change_df = housing_df[housing_df['Year'] >= 2010]
percent_change_df = percent_change_df[percent_change_df['Year'] <= 2018]
hpi_changes = []
county_change = []
percent_change_df.reset_index(inplace=True)

for index, row in percent_change_df.iterrows():
    if index < percent_change_df.shape[0] - 1:
        original = percent_change_df.iloc[index]['HPI with 2000 base']
        next_year_val = percent_change_df.iloc[index + 1]['HPI with 2000 base']
        percent_change = ((next_year_val - original)/original) * 100
        current_county = percent_change_df.iloc[index]['County']
        next_county = percent_change_df.iloc[index + 1]['County']
        if current_county == next_county:
            county_change.append(percent_change)
        else:
            hpi_changes.append(county_change)
            county_change = []

Next, we perform similar calculations for the income dataset, calculating change in median income for each county by year. We also use the 2-dimensional array approach in these calculations.

In [130]:
# Same as above, but this is for income
income_changes = []
county_change = []
for colName, col in income_df.iteritems():
    if colName != "Year" and colName != "Data" and colName != "MARYLAND": 
        idx = 0
        for income in col:
            if idx < income_df.shape[0] - 1:
                next_year_income = income_df.iloc[idx + 1][colName]
                percent_change = ((next_year_income - income)/income) * 100
                county_change.append(percent_change)
                idx += 1
        income_changes.append(county_change)
        county_change = []

Finally, we plot the data we calculated into a double bar graph for each county. For each county, we plot the percent change in HPI vs percent change in median personal income by year. By plotting these against each other, we can demonstrate if the home appreciation parallels median income. Each county is vastly different from one another. For example, in Baltimore County, beginning in the year 2013, the HPI index and median personal income are both increasing, but the median personal income grew much more rapidly than the HPI index. Conversely, in Harford County, in 2017, the median income largely decreased while the HIP index increased 2 percent, meaning that the houses were more expensive than affordable for people earning around the median income. This kind of data assists in demonstrating the patterns of financial affordability in terms of cost of living in different counties of Maryland. After synthesizing the data that we explored, the next step is to test a hypothesis.

Part Four: Hypothesis Testing¶

Hypothesis testing is a statistical method of determining if your created model is a good fit or not. As the name indicates, in hypothesis testing you will have two hypotheses: a null hypothesis and an alternative hypothesis. You want to set up your hypothesis such that you reject the null hypothesis. What does it mean to reject the hypothesis though? This is where significance level comes into the picture. When setting up your experiment, in addition to the hypotheses, you set a significance level. If the p value of your random varaiable in within your siginficance level, also known as the rejection level, you reject the null hypothesis. While determining whether to reject your null hypothesis or not, be careful to determine what type of test you are setting up; is it one-tailed or two-tailed?

UsingHypothesis Testing, we try to interpret or draw conclusions about the population using sample data. In the following code, we explore the relationship between HPI index and median personal income by county using regression lines. Earlier, we visualized the percent change through bar graphs, and made generalized assumptions about the data. Now, we will graph the data in scatter plots and create regression lines to establish the numerical existence of a relationship and the implications of our results.

The code below creates scatter plots for each year from the years 2010-2018, and uses the counties HPI index and the Median Income for that county to try and see if there is a relationship between the HPI index and the median income. After the scatter plot is created, a linear regression line is fit on the data to see if there is a linear relationship between the two values.

In [214]:
hpi_counties = housing_df['County'].unique()
for year in [2010, 2011, 2012, 2013, 2014, 2015, 2016, 2017, 2018]:
    idx = 0
    for county in counties:
        income_row = income_df.loc[income_df['Year'] == year]
        income = income_row[county]
        hpi_row = housing_df.loc[housing_df['Year'] == year]
        hpi_temp = hpi_row[hpi_row['County'] == hpi_counties[idx]]
        hpi = hpi_temp["HPI with 2000 base"]
        idx += 1
        plt.scatter(x=hpi, y=income, label=county)
    
    hpi_rows = percent_change_df[percent_change_df['Year'] == year]
    hpi = np.array(hpi_rows['HPI with 2000 base']).reshape(-1, 1)
    income_row = income_df[income_df['Year'] == year]
    income = np.array(income_row.values[0][3:]).reshape(-1, 1)
    
    reg = LinearRegression().fit(hpi, income)
    plt.plot(hpi, reg.intercept_ + reg.coef_ * hpi, '-')
    plt.xlabel("HPI")
    plt.ylabel("Median Income")
    plt.title("HPI vs Median Income in " + str(year))
    plt.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc='upper left')
    plt.show()

Part Five: Communication of Insights¶

After conducting the hypothesis test, and creating linear regression models to fit the scatterplots, we are surprised to notice little correlation between HPI Index and median personal income. At the most, there is occasionally a concerning slightly negative correlation between the two in some counties: as HPI Index increases, median person income decreases. From our understanding of the variables as related to affordability, we believe that income should be positively proportional to house price appreciation; as prices increases, the cost of living should be comfortable affordable to residents. This finding inspired us to consider a couple of questions to deep dive into for a future project: If not mainly by cost of living, how is income determined, and vice versa? What is the impact of this lack of/slightly negative correlations, and what does this suggest for the future demographic of people in Maryland?

It is clear that our research is not sufficient to solve the issues surrounding income in the economy, but we are able to communicate a meaningful discussion about the affordability of the housing market in Maryland based on our results. The purpose of this tutorial is to demonstrate the application of the Data Science pipeline, and we hope you learned something new!
